The paper deals with pseudorandomness and Fourier analysis of branching programs, which are fundamental objects in computational complexity theory. The focus is on width-3, oblivious, read-once branching programs, which are a well-studied model in the field. Therefore, cs.CC (Computational Complexity) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves cryptography and randomness, which suggests cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) as another likely sub-category. The use of Fourier analysis and the study of Fourier growth bounds suggest cs.IT (Information Theory) as a possible sub-category. The paper also involves the analysis of combinatorial structures, which suggests cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) as possible sub-categories.
